Title : Kemnal Park Cemetery & Memorial Gardens
Text : {{Orphan|date=May 2014}}

 <!-- Do not remove this line! -->

[[File:Kemnal Park Cemetery non-denominational chapel.jpg|thumb|Kemnal Park Cemetery, non-denominational chapel.]][[File:Kemnal Park Cemetery, Monument to the Unknown Parishioner of the Borough of Southwark.jpg|thumb|Kemnal Park Cemetery, Monument to the Unknown Parishioner of the Borough of Southwark.]]'''Kemnal Park Cemetery & Memorial Gardens''' is a privately owned [[cemetery]] in [[London]] that was opened in October 2013 by the Mayor of [[Bromley]], Cllr Ernest Noad.<ref>{{cite web|last=|title=Kemnal Park Cemetery, Chislehurst, open for business|url=http://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/kemnal_park_cemetery_chislehurst_open_for_business_but_how_long_can_graveyard_overpopulation_be_kept_at_bay_1_2954298|publisher=Bromley Times|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref> It comprises 55 acres in total and in addition to the available 30,000 burial plots, features a garden of remembrance, a non-denominational chapel and car parking.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exploring Kemnal Park Cemetery|url=http://www.kemnalpark.org/the-grounds/}}</ref> Near to the cemetery entrance is a monument to ‘the Unknown Parishioner of the Borough of Southwark’. This person’s remains were moved to the cemetery from the former St Saviour's Almshouse burial ground during the construction of the [[Thameslink Programme]] rail project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cathedral holds funeral for Unknown Parishioner |url=http://www.southwark.anglican.org/news/pr/pr.php?id=2115 |publisher=The Diocese of Southwark |accessdate=June 14, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728220151/http://southwark.anglican.org/news/pr/pr.php?id=2115 |archivedate=July 28, 2012 |df= }}</ref> The cemetery is also listed as a 'site of special interest' due to its ancient woodland and diverse bird life.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chislehurst Conservation Area|url=http://www.chislehurst-society.org.uk/Chislehurst%20Conservation%20document.pdf}}</ref> In April 2014, Kemnal Park became the first cemetery in the UK to offer live web streaming of services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Can't make a funeral? Watch it on your phone!|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2600477/Cant-make-funeral-Watch-phone-Cemetery-offer-4G-video-feed-graveside-services.html|publisher=Daily Mail Online|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref>

==Location==
The cemetery is located near [[Chislehurst]] ([[London Borough of Bromley]]) and is adjacent to the south-westerly side of the A20 Sidcup Bypass. It is approximately 5.5 miles WNW of Junction 3 of the [[M25 motorway]].

==History==
The cemetery is located in what was previously the Kemnal House Estate.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Chislehurst|url=http://www.chislehurst.co.uk/history/kemnal-manor/}}</ref> A series of houses were built in this location, the first being mentioned in deeds in 1250 and the last being destroyed by fire in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Kemnal Manor|url=http://www.kemnal-road.org.uk/Pages/Houses/KemnalManor.html}}</ref> From 1964 until work on the new cemetery commenced, the site remained derelict.

